[2
From: Paul Axelsen <axelsen@axe1.med.upenn.edu>
Date: Sat, 15 May 1999 11:21:20 -0400

There is no real conflict between these statements. The good match between
circulating viral strains and vaccine composition is a perfectly reasonable
observation that says nothing about the virulence of the circulating
strains, the immunogenicity of the vaccine, the extent of vaccine use in a
population, or any other factors that bear on the fatality rate due to
influenza.
One factor is that influenza vaccine coverage is never universal. Aside
from passive noncompliance, there are a variety of reasons people may
decide to not receive the vaccine including hypersensitivity to eggs and
religious conviction. Furthermore, even if the vaccine is given, it may
not be effective in immunodeficiency states such as AIDS.
Another factor is that influenza vaccination is not 100% protective against
disease, although it certainly prevents disease in many individuals, and
there is good reason to believe that it mitigates disease in individuals
who might otherwise suffer a more severe course.
Finally, it should be noted that the data reported by the CDC is "mortality
as a percentage of all deaths", and by this measure it is clear that the
influenza season was deadlier than usual not only this year, but also in
the past several years (see
<http://www.cdc.gov/epo/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm4818a2.htm>). However,
this statistic does not address the case-fatality rate among vaccinated
persons. If this were higher than usual, it would raise doubts about the
quality of the match between circulating strains and vaccine composition.
But I know of no data even suggesting that this years vaccine is
significantly less effective than expected.
--
Paul H. Axelsen MD
Departments of Pharmacology and
Medicine, Infectious Diseases Section
University of Pennsylvania
Philadelphia, PA
e-mail: axe@pharm.med.upenn.edu
