[3
Date: Fri, 21 May 1999 07:56:36 -0500
From: David Lawrance <lawrance@uiuc.edu>

Virulence and immunization effectiveness are unrelated issues, so the
reports are not necessarily conflicting. We have no doubt that virulence
felt greater this year than last years. Two other considerations for our
large number of cases: We weren't able to get as many vaccinations out this
year as last, despite intense marketting. Our flu season a year ago was
pretty mild, so I think many of our patients just incorrectly assumed that
they were naturally immune and skipped vaccination. Second our flu season
was later than usual, so levels of protection may have been lower in those
immunized early. However, few of our cases had been immunized, supporting
evidence that the vaccine was effective.
--
David P. Lawrance, MD
Medical Director
McKinley Health Center
University of Illinois at UC
1109 S. Lincoln Avenue
Urbana, IL 61801
e-mail: lawrance@uiuc.edu
[As seems to be the case for many influenza issues, the cup is either half
full or half empty depending on where you sit. Although many countries have
carefully worked out public health policies to prevent and control
influenza, it is still a leading cause of death in most or all of them.
Because of clinical and epidemiologic difficulties, we do not really know
how many influenza deaths occur annually. In the U.S. we look for
excess P & I mortality trends (excess deaths due to either pneumonia,
influenza, or both) based on death certificates filed in major cities.
Since influenza epidemics often occur during incidence peaks of other
respiratory organisms, and since precise microbial diagnosis is rarely
obtained, let alone entered onto death certificates correctly and in timely
fashion, it is not possible to say how much of the excess mortality is "P"
and how much is "I". [Added: Moreover, as readers astutely note, neither
virulence (nor pathogenicity) are necessarily related to vaccine efficacy,
let alone vaccine use in a population setting. Influenza mortality may be
high even when the best vaccines are available. Under the best of
circumstances, with the optimum usage of the best licensed vaccines, and
optimally matched circulating influenza A and B strains, high excess
mortality occurs every year. This is hardly news in the journalistic sense
of the word. On the other hand, would we tolerate this extraordinarily
high mortality from any other disease? Think of the public and public
health concern over Lyme disease, legionellosis, hantavirus pulmonary
syndrome, or an imported-Ebola scare, none of which have killed, over the
long term, even a fraction as
many people.
As several observers noted, the AP story was essentially hyped. It said
"The U.S. flu season was... deadlier than usual this year..." when it
should have said "every year the U.S. has a flu season, and every year this
flu season is deadlier than usual". Expect the same hype next year too.
David M. Morens, M.D.
ProMED-mail Moderator for Influenza
e-mail: dm270q@nih.gov
